        <link rel="schema.DC" href="https://purl.org/DC/elements/1.0/" /><meta name="citation_journal_title" content="RadioGraphics" /><meta name="dc.Title" content="Missed Breast Cancer: Effects of Subconscious Bias and Lesion                    Characteristics" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Leslie                        R.  Lamb" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Marina  Mohallem Fonseca" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Raman  Verma" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Jean                        M.  Seely" /><meta name="dc.Description" content="Radiologists should be knowledgeable of the various unconscious biases that influence breast imaging interpretations, as these can lead to missed breast cancers and misinterpreted breast lesions." /><meta name="Description" content="Radiologists should be knowledgeable of the various unconscious biases that influence breast imaging interpretations, as these can lead to missed breast cancers and misinterpreted breast lesions." /><meta name="dc.Description" content="Medical errors are a substantial cause of morbidity and mortality and the third leading cause of death in the United States. Errors resulting in missed breast cancer are the most common reason for ..." /><meta name="Description" content="Medical errors are a substantial cause of morbidity and mortality and the third leading cause of death in the United States. Errors resulting in missed breast cancer are the most common reason for ..." /><meta name="dc.Publisher" content=" Radiological Society of North America " /><meta name="dc.Date" scheme="WTN8601" content="2020-06-12" /><meta name="dc.Type" content="research-article" /><meta name="dc.Format" content="text/HTML" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="manuscript" content="190090" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="doi" content="10.1148/rg.2020190090" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="url" content="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020190090" /><meta name="dc.Source" content="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020