</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Medical errors are a substantial cause of morbidity and mortality and the third leading cause of death in the United States. Errors resulting in missed breast cancer are the most common reason for medical malpractice lawsuits against all physicians. Missed breast cancers are breast malignancies that are detectable at retrospective review of a previously obtained mammogram that was prospectively reported as showing negative, benign, or probably benign findings. Investigators in prior studies have found that up to 35% of both interval cancers and screen-detected cancers could be classified as missed. As such, in conjunction with having awareness of the most common misleading appearances of breast cancer, it is important to understand the cognitive processes and unconscious biases that can impact image interpretation, thereby helping to decrease the number of missed breast cancers. The various cognitive processes that lead to unconscious bias in breast imaging, such as satisfaction of search, inattention blindness, hindsight, anchoring, premature closing, and satisfaction of reporting, are outlined in this pictorial review of missed breast cancers. In addition, strategies for reducing the rates of these missed cancers are highlighted. The most commonly missed and misinterpreted lesions, including stable lesions, benign-appearing masses, one-view findings, developing asymmetries, subtle calcifications, and architectural distortion, also are reviewed. This information will help illustrate why and how breast cancers are missed and aid in the development of appropriate minimization strategies in breast imaging.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190090">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190090">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) Mediolateral oblique (MLO) (a) and craniocaudal (CC) (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 60-year-old woman show a 12-o’clock–position middle depth mass (circle) in the left breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, estrogen receptor (ER)– and progesterone receptor (PR)–positive, human epidermal growth factor 2 (HER2)–negative, stage T1c (1.9-cm) N1M0 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). No additional findings were detected prospectively, and preoperative MRI was not performed. (d) CC mammographic view shows the mammographically guided breast localization wire in place. Final histopathologic analysis revealed multifocal malignancy with clear but close margins. Subsequent retrospective review of the initially obtained mammograms (a, b) revealed upper outer quadrant architectural distortion (arrows in a, b). (e) Corresponding axial contrast material–enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image shows a suspicious mass with nonmass enhancement (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T2 (4.0-cm) invasive lobular carcinoma (ILC)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig1a.jpeg" height="2042" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique (MLO) <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal (CC) <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 60-year-old woman show a 12-o’clock–position middle depth mass (circle) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, estrogen receptor (ER)– and progesterone receptor (PR)–positive, human epidermal growth factor 2 (HER2)–negative, stage T1c (1.9-cm) N1M0 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). No additional findings were detected prospectively, and preoperative MRI was not performed. <b>(d)</b> CC mammographic view shows the mammographically guided breast localization wire in place. Final histopathologic analysis revealed multifocal malignancy with clear but close margins. Subsequent retrospective review of the initially obtained mammograms <b>(a, b)</b> revealed upper outer quadrant architectural distortion (arrows in a, b). <b>(e)</b> Corresponding axial contrast material–enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image shows a suspicious mass with nonmass enhancement (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T2 (4.0-cm) invasive lobular carcinoma (ILC).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) Mediolateral oblique (MLO) (a) and craniocaudal (CC) (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 60-year-old woman show a 12-o’clock–position middle depth mass (circle) in the left breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, estrogen receptor (ER)– and progesterone receptor (PR)–positive, human epidermal growth factor 2 (HER2)–negative, stage T1c (1.9-cm) N1M0 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). No additional findings were detected prospectively, and preoperative MRI was not performed. (d) CC mammographic view shows the mammographically guided breast localization wire in place. Final histopathologic analysis revealed multifocal malignancy with clear but close margins. Subsequent retrospective review of the initially obtained mammograms (a, b) revealed upper outer quadrant architectural distortion (arrows in a, b). (e) Corresponding axial contrast material–enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image shows a suspicious mass with nonmass enhancement (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T2 (4.0-cm) invasive lobular carcinoma (ILC)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig1b.jpeg" height="2042" width="1276" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique (MLO) <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal (CC) <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 60-year-old woman show a 12-o’clock–position middle depth mass (circle) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, estrogen receptor (ER)– and progesterone receptor (PR)–positive, human epidermal growth factor 2 (HER2)–negative, stage T1c (1.9-cm) N1M0 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). No additional findings were detected prospectively, and preoperative MRI was not performed. <b>(d)</b> CC mammographic view shows the mammographically guided breast localization wire in place. Final histopatholog