ure 1e</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique (MLO) <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal (CC) <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 60-year-old woman show a 12-o’clock–position middle depth mass (circle) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, estrogen receptor (ER)– and progesterone receptor (PR)–positive, human epidermal growth factor 2 (HER2)–negative, stage T1c (1.9-cm) N1M0 invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). No additional findings were detected prospectively, and preoperative MRI was not performed. <b>(d)</b> CC mammographic view shows the mammographically guided breast localization wire in place. Final histopathologic analysis revealed multifocal malignancy with clear but close margins. Subsequent retrospective review of the initially obtained mammograms <b>(a, b)</b> revealed upper outer quadrant architectural distortion (arrows in a, b). <b>(e)</b> Corresponding axial contrast material–enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image shows a suspicious mass with nonmass enhancement (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T2 (4.0-cm) invasive lobular carcinoma (ILC).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 73-year-old woman show a mass (circle) at the 9-o’clock anterior depth position in the right breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a cyst, which was initially thought to be the correlate. (d) Subsequently obtained antiradial US image reveals a suspicious mass (arrow) that correlates with the correct size and location of the mammographic abnormality in a and b. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (9-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig2a.jpeg" height="2032" width="1373" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 73-year-old woman show a mass (circle) at the 9-o’clock anterior depth position in the right breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a cyst, which was initially thought to be the correlate. <b>(d)</b> Subsequently obtained antiradial US image reveals a suspicious mass (arrow) that correlates with the correct size and location of the mammographic abnormality in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (9-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 73-year-old woman show a mass (circle) at the 9-o’clock anterior depth position in the right breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a cyst, which was initially thought to be the correlate. (d) Subsequently obtained antiradial US image reveals a suspicious mass (arrow) that correlates with the correct size and location of the mammographic abnormality in a and b. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (9-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig2b.jpeg" height="2032" width="1375" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 73-year-old woman show a mass (circle) at the 9-o’clock anterior depth position in the right breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a cyst, which was initially thought to be the correlate. <b>(d)</b> Subsequently obtained antiradial US image reveals a suspicious mass (arrow) that correlates with the correct size and location of the mammographic abnormality in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (9-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 73-year-old woman show a mass (circle) at the 9-o’clock anterior depth position in the right breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a cyst, which was initially thought to be the correlate. (d) Subsequently obtained antiradial US image reveals a suspicious mass (arrow) that correlates with the correct size and location of the mammographic abnormality in a and b. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (9-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig2c.jpeg" height="972" width="1634" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 73-year-old woman show a mass (circle) at the 9-o’clock anterior depth position in the right breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a cyst, which was initially thought to be the correlate. <b>(d)</b> Subsequently obtained antiradial US image reveals a suspicious mass (arrow) that correlates with the correct size and location of the mammographic abnormality in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (9-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 73-year-old woman show a mass (circle) at the 9-o’clock anterior depth position in the right breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a cyst, which was initially thought to be the correlate. (d) Subsequently obtained antiradial US image reveals a suspicious mass (arrow) that correlates with the correct size and location of the mammographic abnormality in a and b. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (9-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig2d.jpeg" height="982" width="1514" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 73-year-old woman show a mass (circle) at the 9-o’clock anterior depth position in the right breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a cyst, which was initially thought to be the correlate. <b>(d)</b> Subsequently obtained antiradial US image reveals a suspicious mass (arrow) that correlates with the correct size and location of the mammographic abnormality in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (9-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 51-year-old woman show an asymmetry (arrow in a) in the inferior, far posterior region of the left breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 3; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1c (1.7-cm) N1M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig3a.jpeg" height="2411" width="1569" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 51-year-old woman show an asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the inferior, far posterior region of the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 3; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1c (1.7-cm) N1M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 51-year-old woman show an asymmetry (arrow in a) in the inferior, far posterior region of the left breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 3; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1c (1.7-cm) N1M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig3b.jpeg" height="2411" width="1184" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 51-year-old woman show an asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the inferior, far posterior region of the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 3; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1c (1.7-cm) N1M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views obtained in a 51-year-old woman show an asymmetry (arrow in a) in the inferior, far posterior region of the left breast. (c) Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 3; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1c (1.7-cm) N1M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig3c.jpeg" height="1330" width="1797" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in a 51-year-old woman show an asymmetry (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the inferior, far posterior region of the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding transverse US image shows a suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 3; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1c (1.7-cm) N1M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="(a) MLO diagnostic mammographic view in a 58-year-old woman with no prior history of surgery shows left nipple retraction and a retroareolar spiculated mass (circle) with axillary lymphadenopathy (arrow). (b) CC magnification view of the retroareolar region shows associated pleomorphic calcifications (arrow). (c) Radial US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). (d, e) MLO mammographic view (d) shows that in retrospect, asymmetric left nipple retraction and focal asymmetry (circle; CC view not shown) were present 5 years previously, when compared to the right breast and nipple depicted on the MLO mammographic view (e). Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 2.9-cm IDC with ductal and lobular features, as well as axillary nodal and osseous metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig4a.jpeg" height="1413" width="944" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. <b>(a)</b> MLO diagnostic mammographic view in a 58-year-old woman with no prior history of surgery shows left nipple retraction and a retroareolar spiculated mass (circle) with axillary lymphadenopathy (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CC magnification view of the retroareolar region shows associated pleomorphic calcifications (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Radial US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MLO mammographic view <b>(d)</b> shows that in retrospect, asymmetric left nipple retraction and focal asymmetry (circle; CC view not shown) were present 5 years previously, when compared to the right breast and nipple depicted on the MLO mammographic view <b>(e)</b>. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 2.9-cm IDC with ductal and lobular features, as well as axillary nodal and osseous metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="(a) MLO diagnostic mammographic view in a 58-year-old woman with no prior history of surgery shows left nipple retraction and a retroareolar spiculated mass (circle) with axillary lymphadenopathy (arrow). (b) CC magnification view of the retroareolar region shows associated pleomorphic calcifications (arrow). (c) Radial US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). (d, e) MLO mammographic view (d) shows that in retrospect, asymmetric left nipple retraction and focal asymmetry (circle; CC view not shown) were present 5 years previously, when compared to the right breast and nipple depicted on the MLO mammographic view (e). Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 2.9-cm IDC with ductal and lobular features, as well as axillary nodal and osseous metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig4b.jpeg" height="1413" width="901" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. <b>(a)</b> MLO diagnostic mammographic view in a 58-year-old woman with no prior history of surgery shows left nipple retraction and a retroareolar spiculated mass (circle) with axillary lymphadenopathy (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CC magnification view of the retroareolar region shows associated pleomorphic calcifications (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Radial US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). <b>(d, e)</b> MLO mammographic view <b>(d)</b> shows that in retrospect, asymmetric left nipple retraction and focal asymmetry (circle; CC view not shown) were present 5 years previously, when compared to the right breast and nipple depicted on the MLO mammographic view <b>(e)</b>. Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 2.9-cm IDC with ductal and lobular features, as well as axillary nodal and osseous metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFig