sverse US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). (d) Contrast-enhanced maximal intensity projection MR image shows extensive multicentric disease (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T3, N0M0 ILC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig5c.jpeg" height="976" width="1205" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show a 3-o’clock–position posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the retroglandular clear space (no-man’s- land) of the right breast. <b>(c)</b> Transverse US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximal intensity projection MR image shows extensive multicentric disease (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T3, N0M0 ILC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show a 3-o’clock–position posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow in b) in the retroglandular clear space (no-man’s- land) of the right breast. (c) Transverse US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). (d) Contrast-enhanced maximal intensity projection MR image shows extensive multicentric disease (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T3, N0M0 ILC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig5d.jpeg" height="978" width="1948" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show a 3-o’clock–position posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the retroglandular clear space (no-man’s- land) of the right breast. <b>(c)</b> Transverse US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximal intensity projection MR image shows extensive multicentric disease (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T3, N0M0 ILC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="(a–c) MLO (a) and CC (b) mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show an upper outer quadrant, posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow) in the area parallel with the edge of the pectoralis major muscle (“Milky Way”) of the left breast that persists with compression (c). (d) Transverse US image shows an oval circumscribed mass (arrow) with apparent intralesional fat. Based on suspicious mammographic imaging findings, a stereotactic biopsy was performed, revealing grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (7-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig6a.jpeg" height="2120" width="913" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show an upper outer quadrant, posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow) in the area parallel with the edge of the pectoralis major muscle (“Milky Way”) of the left breast that persists with compression <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Transverse US image shows an oval circumscribed mass (arrow) with apparent intralesional fat. Based on suspicious mammographic imaging findings, a stereotactic biopsy was performed, revealing grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (7-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="(a–c) MLO (a) and CC (b) mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show an upper outer quadrant, posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow) in the area parallel with the edge of the pectoralis major muscle (“Milky Way”) of the left breast that persists with compression (c). (d) Transverse US image shows an oval circumscribed mass (arrow) with apparent intralesional fat. Based on suspicious mammographic imaging findings, a stereotactic biopsy was performed, revealing grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (7-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig6b.jpeg" height="2120" width="964" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show an upper outer quadrant, posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow) in the area parallel with the edge of the pectoralis major muscle (“Milky Way”) of the left breast that persists with compression <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Transverse US image shows an oval circumscribed mass (arrow) with apparent intralesional fat. Based on suspicious mammographic imaging findings, a stereotactic biopsy was performed, revealing grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (7-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="(a–c) MLO (a) and CC (b) mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show an upper outer quadrant, posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow) in the area parallel with the edge of the pectoralis major muscle (“Milky Way”) of the left breast that persists with compression (c). (d) Transverse US image shows an oval circumscribed mass (arrow) with apparent intralesional fat. Based on suspicious mammographic imaging findings, a stereotactic biopsy was performed, revealing grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (7-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig6c.jpeg" height="2120" width="825" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show an upper outer quadrant, posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow) in the area parallel with the edge of the pectoralis major muscle (“Milky Way”) of the left breast that persists with compression <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Transverse US image shows an oval circumscribed mass (arrow) with apparent intralesional fat. Based on suspicious mammographic imaging findings, a stereotactic biopsy was performed, revealing grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (7-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic" aria-label="(a–c) MLO (a) and CC (b) mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show an upper outer quadrant, posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow) in the area parallel with the edge of the pectoralis major muscle (“Milky Way”) of the left breast that persists with compression (c). (d) Transverse US image shows an oval circumscribed mass (arrow) with apparent intralesional fat. Based on suspicious mammographic imaging findings, a stereotactic biopsy was performed, revealing grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (7-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig6d.jpeg" height="912" width="1796" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman show an upper outer quadrant, posterior depth focal asymmetry (arrow) in the area parallel with the edge of the pectoralis major muscle (“Milky Way”) of the left breast that persists with compression <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Transverse US image shows an oval circumscribed mass (arrow) with apparent intralesional fat. Based on suspicious mammographic imaging findings, a stereotactic biopsy was performed, revealing grade 1, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1b (7-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="Anchoring bias involving the diagnosis in a 28-year-old woman with breast inflammation and purulent nipple drainage 1 month after a right nipple piercing. The inflammation and nipple drainage did not improve with antibiotics. Mammography was not performed. (a) Transverse US image in the retroareolar region shows a finding that was reported as a complex fluid collection adjacent to the piercing (BALL), which was attributed a BI-RADS 3 category and presumed to represent mastitis with an abscess. The patient was treated with additional antibiotics, the fluid collection was drained, and the nipple piercing was removed. (b, c) Transverse US images obtained at 3-month follow-up shows findings that were reported as a complex fluid collection and an inflammed mass (b), with suspected reactive lymph nodes (c). These findings were assigned a BI-RADS 3 category. The primary care physician was concerned about worsening symptoms, prompting a skin punch biopsy, which demonstrated malignancy. (d) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 3 months after follow-up shows masses and diffuse nonmass enhancement (arrow) with skin and pectoral muscle involvement. Histopathologic analysis revealed locally advanced, inflammatory grade 3, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 11.2-cm IDC, as well as axillary nodal, osseous, hepatic, and pulmonary metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig7a.jpeg" height="969" width="1522" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Anchoring bias involving the diagnosis in a 28-year-old woman with breast inflammation and purulent nipple drainage 1 month after a right nipple piercing. The inflammation and nipple drainage did not improve with antibiotics. Mammography was not performed. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image in the retroareolar region shows a finding that was reported as a complex fluid collection adjacent to the piercing <i>(BALL),</i> which was attributed a BI-RADS 3 category and presumed to represent mastitis with an abscess. The patient was treated with additional antibiotics, the fluid collection was drained, and the nipple piercing was removed. <b>(b, c)</b> Transverse US images obtained at 3-month follow-up shows findings that were reported as a complex fluid collection and an inflammed mass <b>(b)</b>, with suspected reactive lymph nodes <b>(c)</b>. These findings were assigned a BI-RADS 3 category. The primary care physician was concerned about worsening symptoms, prompting a skin punch biopsy, which demonstrated malignancy. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 3 months after follow-up shows masses and diffuse nonmass enhancement (arrow) with skin and pectoral muscle involvement. Histopathologic analysis revealed locally advanced, inflammatory grade 3, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 11.2-cm IDC, as well as axillary nodal, osseous, hepatic, and pulmonary metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="Anchoring bias involving the diagnosis in a 28-year-old woman with breast inflammation and purulent nipple drainage 1 month after a right nipple piercing. The inflammation and nipple drainage did not improve with antibiotics. Mammography was not performed. (a) Transverse US image in the retroareolar region shows a finding that was reported as a complex fluid collection adjacent to the piercing (BALL), which was attributed a BI-RADS 3 category and presumed to represent mastitis with an abscess. The patient was treated with additional antibiotics, the fluid collection was drained, and the nipple piercing was removed. (b, c) Transverse US images obtained at 3-month follow-up shows findings that were reported as a complex fluid collection and an inflammed mass (b), with suspected reactive lymph nodes (c). These findings were assigned a BI-RADS 3 category. The primary care physician was concerned about worsening symptoms, prompting a skin punch biopsy, which demonstrated malignancy. (d) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 3 months after follow-up shows masses and diffuse nonmass enhancement (arrow) with skin and pectoral muscle involvement. Histopathologic analysis revealed locally advanced, inflammatory grade 3, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 11.2-cm IDC, as well as axillary nodal, osseous, hepatic, and pulmonary metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig7b.jpeg" height="969" width="1627" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Anchoring bias involving the diagnosis in a 28-year-old woman with breast inflammation and purulent nipple drainage 1 month after a right nipple piercing. The inflammation and nipple drainage did not improve with antibiotics. Mammography was not performed. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image in the retroareolar region shows a finding that was reported as a complex fluid collection adjacent to the piercing <i>(BALL),</i> which was attributed a BI-RADS 3 category and presumed to represent mastitis with an abscess. The patient was treated with additional antibiotics, the fluid collection was drained, and the nipple piercing was removed. <b>(b, c)</b> Transverse US images obtained at 3-month follow-up shows findings that were reported as a complex fluid collection and an inflammed mass <b>(b)</b>, with suspected reactive lymph nodes <b>(c)</b>. These findings were assigned a BI-RADS 3 category. The primary care physician was concerned about worsening symptoms, prompting a skin punch biopsy, which demonstrated malignancy. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 3 months after follow-up shows masses and diffuse nonmass enhancement (arrow) with skin and pectoral muscle involvement. Histopathologic analysis revealed locally advanced, inflammatory grade 3, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 11.2-cm IDC, as well as axillary nodal, osseous, hepatic, and pulmonary metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic" aria-label="Anchoring bias involving the diagnosis in a 28-year-old woman with breast inflammation and purulent nipple drainage 1 month after