al antibiotics, the fluid collection was drained, and the nipple piercing was removed. <b>(b, c)</b> Transverse US images obtained at 3-month follow-up shows findings that were reported as a complex fluid collection and an inflammed mass <b>(b)</b>, with suspected reactive lymph nodes <b>(c)</b>. These findings were assigned a BI-RADS 3 category. The primary care physician was concerned about worsening symptoms, prompting a skin punch biopsy, which demonstrated malignancy. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 3 months after follow-up shows masses and diffuse nonmass enhancement (arrow) with skin and pectoral muscle involvement. Histopathologic analysis revealed locally advanced, inflammatory grade 3, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 11.2-cm IDC, as well as axillary nodal, osseous, hepatic, and pulmonary metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic" aria-label="Anchoring bias involving the diagnosis in a 28-year-old woman with breast inflammation and purulent nipple drainage 1 month after a right nipple piercing. The inflammation and nipple drainage did not improve with antibiotics. Mammography was not performed. (a) Transverse US image in the retroareolar region shows a finding that was reported as a complex fluid collection adjacent to the piercing (BALL), which was attributed a BI-RADS 3 category and presumed to represent mastitis with an abscess. The patient was treated with additional antibiotics, the fluid collection was drained, and the nipple piercing was removed. (b, c) Transverse US images obtained at 3-month follow-up shows findings that were reported as a complex fluid collection and an inflammed mass (b), with suspected reactive lymph nodes (c). These findings were assigned a BI-RADS 3 category. The primary care physician was concerned about worsening symptoms, prompting a skin punch biopsy, which demonstrated malignancy. (d) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 3 months after follow-up shows masses and diffuse nonmass enhancement (arrow) with skin and pectoral muscle involvement. Histopathologic analysis revealed locally advanced, inflammatory grade 3, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 11.2-cm IDC, as well as axillary nodal, osseous, hepatic, and pulmonary metastases."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig7d.jpeg" height="915" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Anchoring bias involving the diagnosis in a 28-year-old woman with breast inflammation and purulent nipple drainage 1 month after a right nipple piercing. The inflammation and nipple drainage did not improve with antibiotics. Mammography was not performed. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image in the retroareolar region shows a finding that was reported as a complex fluid collection adjacent to the piercing <i>(BALL),</i> which was attributed a BI-RADS 3 category and presumed to represent mastitis with an abscess. The patient was treated with additional antibiotics, the fluid collection was drained, and the nipple piercing was removed. <b>(b, c)</b> Transverse US images obtained at 3-month follow-up shows findings that were reported as a complex fluid collection and an inflammed mass <b>(b)</b>, with suspected reactive lymph nodes <b>(c)</b>. These findings were assigned a BI-RADS 3 category. The primary care physician was concerned about worsening symptoms, prompting a skin punch biopsy, which demonstrated malignancy. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 3 months after follow-up shows masses and diffuse nonmass enhancement (arrow) with skin and pectoral muscle involvement. Histopathologic analysis revealed locally advanced, inflammatory grade 3, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, 11.2-cm IDC, as well as axillary nodal, osseous, hepatic, and pulmonary metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. (c) Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). (d, e) Previously obtained MLO (d) and CC (e) mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in d. (f) Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). (g) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig8a.jpeg" height="1389" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). <b>(d, e)</b> Previously obtained MLO <b>(d)</b> and CC <b>(e)</b> mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in <b>d. (f)</b> Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. (c) Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). (d, e) Previously obtained MLO (d) and CC (e) mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in d. (f) Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). (g) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig8b.jpeg" height="1389" width="934" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). <b>(d, e)</b> Previously obtained MLO <b>(d)</b> and CC <b>(e)</b> mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in <b>d. (f)</b> Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. (c) Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). (d, e) Previously obtained MLO (d) and CC (e) mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in d. (f) Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). (g) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig8c.jpeg" height="1010" width="1276" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). <b>(d, e)</b> Previously obtained MLO <b>(d)</b> and CC <b>(e)</b> mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in <b>d. (f)</b> Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. (c) Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). (d, e) Previously obtained MLO (d) and CC (e) mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in d. (f) Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). (g) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig8d.jpeg" height="1389" width="913" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). <b>(d, e)</b> Previously obtained MLO <b>(d)</b> and CC <b>(e)</b> mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in <b>d. (f)</b> Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8e" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. (c) Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). (d, e) Previously obtained MLO (d) and CC (e) mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in d. (f) Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). (g) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig8e.jpeg" height="1389" width="922" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). <b>(d, e)</b> Previously obtained MLO <b>(d)</b> and CC <b>(e)</b> mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in <b>d. (f)</b> Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8f" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. (c) Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). (d, e) Previously obtained MLO (d) and CC (e) mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in d. (f) Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). (g) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig8f.jpeg" height="1022" width="1158" aria-labelledby="fig8f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8f</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). <b>(d, e)</b> Previously obtained MLO <b>(d)</b> and CC <b>(e)</b> mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in <b>d. (f)</b> Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig8f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8g" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. (c) Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). (d, e) Previously obtained MLO (d) and CC (e) mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in d. (f) Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). (g) Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig8g.jpeg" height="1010" width="1261" aria-labelledby="fig8g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8g</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> screening mammographic views in a 64-year-old woman with a history of a contralateral (right) breast malignancy diagnosed 2 years earlier and a benign left lumpectomy (performed in 1977) show a lower inner quadrant, middle depth, focal asymmetry with calcifications (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Magnified synthetic CC mammographic view shows fine pleomorphic calcifications with a linear distribution (circle). <b>(d, e)</b> Previously obtained MLO <b>(d)</b> and CC <b>(e)</b> mammographic views from 2 years earlier show stable findings. A port-a-cath implanted for cancer treatment is shown in <b>d. (f)</b> Transverse US image shows an irregular mass (arrow). <b>(g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtracted MR image obtained 2 years earlier for right breast malignancy retrospectively shows a corresponding spiculated enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. At the time of MR image interpretation, this mass was erroneously attributed to benign changes after remote benign lumpectomy. The right breast retroareolar mass corresponded to the known malignancy (circle). Histopathologic analysis after a 14-gauge core-needle biopsy revealed sclerosing adenosis, cyst formation, apocrine metaplasia, and areas of elastic stroma with small entrapped ducts, suggestive of a complex sclerosing lesion and/or a radial scar but insufficient to make a definitive diagnosis. The pathology results were discordant. Histopathologic analysis after repeat US-guided vacuum-assisted biopsy (performed with a 9-gauge needle) revealed grade 1; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T1a (4-mm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig8g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="(a–f) Multiple MLO (a–c) and CC (d–f) screening mammographic views obtained in 2011 (a, d), 2014 (b, e), and 2018 (c, f) in a 74-year-old woman show a relatively stable focal asymmetry (arrow) in the right breast at the 9-o’clock position, posterior depth. (g) Transverse US image shows a corresponding irregular mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2–3, ER-positive, PR-negative, HER2-negative, multifocal stage T1c (1.3-cm) N1a intramammary node, M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig9a.jpeg" height="2129" width="1202" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. <b>(a–f)</b> Multiple MLO <b>(a–c)</b> and CC <b>(d–f)</b> screening mammographic views obtained in 2011 <b>(a, d)</b>, 2014 <b>(b, e)</b>, and 2018 <b>(c, f)</b> in a 74-year-old woman show a relatively stable focal asymmetry (arrow) in the right breast at the 9-o’clock position, posterior depth. <b>(g)</b> Transverse US image shows a corresponding irregular mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed a grade 2–3, ER-positive, PR-negative, HER2-negative, multifocal stage T1c (1.3-cm) N1a intramammary node, M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi