in a 73-year-old woman from 2009 <b>(a, d)</b>, 2011 <b>(b, e)</b>, and 2013 <b>(c, f)</b> show a developing asymmetry (arrow) in the left breast upper outer quadrant, middle depth. The asymmetry was gradually becoming more conspicuous over time. Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T2 (2.5-cm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12e" class="graphic" aria-label="Multiple MLO (a–c) and CC (d–f) screening mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman from 2009 (a, d), 2011 (b, e), and 2013 (c, f) show a developing asymmetry (arrow) in the left breast upper outer quadrant, middle depth. The asymmetry was gradually becoming more conspicuous over time. Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T2 (2.5-cm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig12e.jpeg" height="1768" width="1180" aria-labelledby="fig12e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12e</span>. Multiple MLO <b>(a–c)</b> and CC <b>(d–f)</b> screening mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman from 2009 <b>(a, d)</b>, 2011 <b>(b, e)</b>, and 2013 <b>(c, f)</b> show a developing asymmetry (arrow) in the left breast upper outer quadrant, middle depth. The asymmetry was gradually becoming more conspicuous over time. Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T2 (2.5-cm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig12e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12f" class="graphic" aria-label="Multiple MLO (a–c) and CC (d–f) screening mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman from 2009 (a, d), 2011 (b, e), and 2013 (c, f) show a developing asymmetry (arrow) in the left breast upper outer quadrant, middle depth. The asymmetry was gradually becoming more conspicuous over time. Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T2 (2.5-cm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig12f.jpeg" height="1772" width="1074" aria-labelledby="fig12f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12f</span>. Multiple MLO <b>(a–c)</b> and CC <b>(d–f)</b> screening mammographic views in a 73-year-old woman from 2009 <b>(a, d)</b>, 2011 <b>(b, e)</b>, and 2013 <b>(c, f)</b> show a developing asymmetry (arrow) in the left breast upper outer quadrant, middle depth. The asymmetry was gradually becoming more conspicuous over time. Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2; ER-, PR-, and HER2-negative; stage T2 (2.5-cm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig12f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="Mediolateral 90° magnification view (a) in a 49-year-old woman shows faint calcifications in a linear distribution (circle in a) in the right breast. Two-dimensional prone-position stereotactic biopsy was attempted but unsuccessful owing to faint visibility. Repeat biopsy was recommended, but the patient declined and opted to undergo 6-month follow-up mammography (b), which revealed an increased number of calcifications (circle in b). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, T1 (3-mm) N0M0 IDC with ductal carcinoma in situ."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig13a.jpeg" height="1635" width="1273" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Mediolateral 90° magnification view <b>(a)</b> in a 49-year-old woman shows faint calcifications in a linear distribution (circle in <b>a</b>) in the right breast. Two-dimensional prone-position stereotactic biopsy was attempted but unsuccessful owing to faint visibility. Repeat biopsy was recommended, but the patient declined and opted to undergo 6-month follow-up mammography <b>(b)</b>, which revealed an increased number of calcifications (circle in <b>b</b>). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, T1 (3-mm) N0M0 IDC with ductal carcinoma in situ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Mediolateral 90° magnification view (a) in a 49-year-old woman shows faint calcifications in a linear distribution (circle in a) in the right breast. Two-dimensional prone-position stereotactic biopsy was attempted but unsuccessful owing to faint visibility. Repeat biopsy was recommended, but the patient declined and opted to undergo 6-month follow-up mammography (b), which revealed an increased number of calcifications (circle in b). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, T1 (3-mm) N0M0 IDC with ductal carcinoma in situ."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig13b.jpeg" height="1635" width="1275" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Mediolateral 90° magnification view <b>(a)</b> in a 49-year-old woman shows faint calcifications in a linear distribution (circle in <b>a</b>) in the right breast. Two-dimensional prone-position stereotactic biopsy was attempted but unsuccessful owing to faint visibility. Repeat biopsy was recommended, but the patient declined and opted to undergo 6-month follow-up mammography <b>(b)</b>, which revealed an increased number of calcifications (circle in <b>b</b>). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, T1 (3-mm) N0M0 IDC with ductal carcinoma in situ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="(a, b) MLO (a) and CC (b) tomosynthesis mammographic views in a 53-year-old woman show subtle architectural distortion (circle) in the upper outer quadrant, posterior depth, in the left breast. (c) Corresponding two-dimensional CC mammographic view is shown for comparison. (d) Transverse US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1 (1.5-cm) N0M0 IDC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190090/asset/images/large/rg.2020190090.fig14a.jpeg" height="2038" width="1170" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> tomosynthesis mammographic views in a 53-year-old woman show subtle architectural distortion (circle) in the upper outer quadrant, posterior depth, in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding two-dimensional CC mammographic view is shown for comparison. <b>(d)</b> Transverse US image shows a corresponding suspicious mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis revealed grade 2, ER- and PR-positive, HER2-negative, stage T1 (1.5-cm) N0M0 IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190090&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><fig